10b5-1 plansEveryone knows how you can abuse 10b5-1 plans, right? Corporate=
 executives are not supposed to trade their company=E2=80=99s stock when th=
ey have inside information. This is sort of a hard rule to follow, since co=
rporate executives are constantly getting inside information to do their jo=
bs, and sometimes they need to sell stock to pay for their kids=E2=80=99 co=
llege or whatever.So U.S. securities law has=C2=A0a rule, Rule 10b5-1(c), w=
hich says that an executive can set up a plan to automatically trade stock.=
 The idea is that, when you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0have inside information=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0say a few days after the company releases earnings, when ev=
erything that you know is (in theory) public =E2=80=94=C2=A0you set up a pl=
an that says =E2=80=9CI will sell 10,000 shares a month for the next 12 mon=
ths=E2=80=9D or whatever. You can make the plan a lot more complicated; it =
can say things like =E2=80=9Cif the stock is above $100 I will sell 10,000 =
shares per month, if it=E2=80=99s between $80 and $100 I=E2=80=99ll sell 5,=
000 shares, if it=E2=80=99s below 80 I=E2=80=99ll sell 1,000 shares,=E2=80=
=9D etc.; it can have all sorts of detailed instructions for your broker fo=
r different eventualities.[2] The point is you sign the plan, you give it t=
o your broker, and then your broker sells the stock for you without any fur=
ther input. So you are free to learn material nonpublic information about y=
our company as part of your job, and your broker is free to sell your stock=
 to pay for your=C2=A0kids=E2=80=99 college. Sensible rule.People are very =
suspicious of these plans. For one thing, people often doubt that executive=
s are=C2=A0actually =E2=80=9Cclean=E2=80=9D of material nonpublic informati=
on when they enter into 10b5-1 plans. Which is fair enough; if you run a co=
mpany you always know something that the public doesn=E2=80=99t. My view is=
 that there has to be=C2=A0some=C2=A0way for executives to sell stock while=
 remaining employed at their companies, and 10b5-1 is a reasonable way to d=
o it, but in any particular case you might wonder if the executive set up t=
he plan in order to dump stock before bad news comes out.For another thing,=
 these plans always seem to take people by surprise? Like a company will an=
nounce bad news, and people will notice that the executives sold stock befo=
re the announcement, and the executives will say =E2=80=9Cwell that was pur=
suant to a 10b5-1 plan,=E2=80=9D and articles about their sales will quote =
that explanation but in a grudging suspicious way. Like the order of events=
 will be (1) executive enters a 10b5-1 plan, (2) executive sells stock auto=
matically, (3) company announces bad news; but=C2=A0the=C2=A0public =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and the media, and shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0will experience tha=
t in reverse. First they will see the bad news, then they will get the shoc=
king information that the executives were=C2=A0selling stock=C2=A0ahead of =
the bad news, and finally they will get the executives=E2=80=99=C2=A0lame e=
xplanation that they had a 10b5-1 plan. It might be better if the executive=
s announced the 10b5-1 plans in advance.=C2=A0Finally, there is the classic=
 way to abuse 10b5-1 plans:=09In March, you have no nonpublic information, =
but you know that you will=C2=A0get nonpublic information in May and announ=
ce it in June. You have a drug trial that will produce positive or negative=
 news, etc.=09You sign up a 10b5-1 plan in March to sell all your stock at =
the end of May.=09At the beginning of May, you get the drug trial results.=
=09If they are good, you cancel the 10b5-1 plan and keep your stock.=09If t=
hey are bad, you do nothing and the 10b5-1 plan automatically sells all you=
r stock.=09In June, you announce the results. If they=E2=80=99re good, the =
stock you kept goes up. If they=E2=80=99re bad, the stock you sold goes dow=
n.The trick is that you are required to be clean of material nonpublic info=
rmation when you=C2=A0enter=C2=A0a 10b5-1 plan, but=C2=A0not when you=C2=A0=
cancel=C2=A0it. You can cancel it for any reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0your kids d=
ropped out of college, you feel like it, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and because ca=
nceling a 10b5-1 plan is not a=C2=A0trade, it=E2=80=99s not insider trading=
.[3]=C2=A0The really advanced move is:=09Again, in March you are =E2=80=9Cc=
lean=E2=80=9D but know that there will be news in May that will be announce=
d in June.=09You sign up a 10b5-1 plan to sell all your stock on May 25.=09=
You sign up=C2=A0another=C2=A010b5-1 plan to=C2=A0buy=C2=A0a bunch of stock=
 on May 30.=09=E2=80=9CWhat, I am doing some complicated tax planning, don=
=E2=80=99t worry about it.=E2=80=9D=09At the beginning of May you get the r=
esults.=09You cancel one plan and do the other one: If the results are good=
, you cancel the sale and do the buy; if they=E2=80=99re bad, you cancel th=
e buy and do the sale.=09Announce the results, profit, etc.To be clear, the=
se classic abuses are absolutely not allowed. The rule says that a 10b5-1 p=
lan is only a defense to insider trading if it =E2=80=9Cwas given or entere=
d into in good faith and not as part of a plan or scheme to evade the prohi=
bitions of this section,=E2=80=9D and most securities lawyers will tell you=
 that if you set up a 10b5-1 plan intending to cancel it if you get good ne=
ws =E2=80=94=C2=A0or set up offsetting plans intending to cancel one depend=
ing on the news =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that is not =E2=80=9Cgood faith.=E2=80=
=9D (Not legal advice!) Still, these things are not easy to check, you can =
probably get away with it once, etc., and the whole thing is just viewed wi=
th a lot of suspicion by a lot of people.Including, now, Gary Gensler, the =
chairman of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission:Speaking Monday at =
The Wall Street Journal=E2=80=99s CFO Network event, SEC Chairman Gary Gens=
ler said he is seeking to revise rules that govern the arrangements, known =
as 10b5-1 plans. =E2=80=A6Mr. Gensler suggested Monday that rule changes ar=
e now due. =E2=80=9CIn my view, these plans have led to real cracks in our =
insider-trading regime,=E2=80=9D he said.Here is the text of his speech, wh=
ich suggests four changes:=09Required =E2=80=9Cfour- to six-month cooling-o=
ff periods=E2=80=9D between the time an executive adopts a plan and the tim=
e when she can start selling, to make sure that she was really clean of ins=
ide information.=09Limitations on canceling plans, to avoid the classic abu=
se:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIn my view, canceling a plan may be as economically signi=
ficant as carrying out an actual transaction. That=E2=80=99s because materi=
al nonpublic information might influence an insider=E2=80=99s decision to c=
ancel an order to sell.=E2=80=9D=09Disclosure requirements, so that shareho=
lders know about 10b5-1 plans before the executives dump all their shares.=
=09=E2=80=9CA limit on the number of 10b5-1 plans,=E2=80=9D to avoid the ad=
vanced move I suggested above: =E2=80=9CWith the ability to enter into mult=
iple plans, and potentially to cancel them, insiders might mistakenly think=
 they have a =E2=80=98free option=E2=80=99 to pick amongst favorable plans =
as they please.=E2=80=9DI tend to think these concerns are a little overblo=
wn, and that anyone who actually entered into multiple plans and then freel=
y canceled them based on inside information would get in trouble anyway. (=
=E2=80=9CMake no mistake,=E2=80=9D says Gensler:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAs the rule =
stands today, canceling or amending any 10b5-1 plans calls into question wh=
ether they were entered into in good faith.=E2=80=9D) But these concerns=C2=
=A0are=C2=A0widely held, and people=C2=A0are suspicious of 10b5-1 plans, an=
d I don=E2=80=99t think it does much harm to address their suspicions.DaveI=
=E2=80=99m sorry, this is not big news and I have nothing interesting to sa=
y about it, but this is the first I=E2=80=99ve heard of it and it=E2=80=99s=
 so funny:A special-purpose acquisition company sponsored by Victory Park C=
apital has agreed to merge with banking app Dave, allowing the financial st=
artup to begin operating as a public company. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CThis transa=
ction and continued support from our longstanding investors signify confide=
nce in our strategy, vision and the significant growth opportunities ahead,=
=E2=80=9D Dave Chief Executive Jason Wilk said.It=E2=80=99s called Dave. =
=E2=80=9CDave Chief Executive Jason Wilk.=E2=80=9D When Goldman Sachs Group=
 Inc. first branded its consumer bank as =E2=80=9CMarcus,=E2=80=9D I made f=
un of its please-Goldman-was-our-father=E2=80=99s-name vibe. =E2=80=9CLife =
is great here,=E2=80=9D  I wrote, =E2=80=9Cin the casual Friday of late cap=
italism.=E2=80=9D But at least Marcus is, like, a full name that might appe=
ar on a birth certificate. (Marcus Goldman=E2=80=99s birth certificate.) It=
 has two whole syllables. Dave is short for David. Dave just seems a little=
 laid-back for someone whom you=E2=80=99re trusting to hold your wallet.=C2=
=A0I wish Dave immense success. I hope Dave becomes the biggest bank in the=
 world. I hope Dave gets into investment banking and derivatives trading. I=
 hope initial public offering prospectuses regularly have =E2=80=9CDave=E2=
=80=9D in the lead left position on the cover. I hope companies announce mu=
ltibillion-dollar mergers and say =E2=80=9CAmalgamated Widgets received fin=
ancial advice from=C2=A0Dave.=E2=80=9D I hope salespeople on the Dave bond =
trading floor regularly answer the phone by saying =E2=80=9CDave, this is M=
att.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CDave, this is Linda.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CDave, this is=
 Dave.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Things happenThe U.S. tax code=C2=A0does not tax unrea=
lized capital gains. Colonial Pipeline=E2=80=99s Bitcoin Ransom  Mostly Rec=
ouped by U.S. Mining Companies Call Themselves Green in Push for Investor C=
ash. Treasuries Tick Higher After  Internet Outage Spooks Markets. SoftBank=
 Throws Final Cash Infusion to Bankrupt Startup  Katerra.=C2=A0MicroStrateg=
y to Sell New Bitcoin Bond. Don=E2=80=99t Eat Cicadas if You=E2=80=99re All=
ergic to Seafood, F.D.A. Warns.=C2=A0Microsoft Excel Esports Tournament Is =
Real And Actually Happening.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=
=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this =
link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newslet=
ters here. Thanks![1] People did not like this use of =E2=80=9Cleverage=E2=
=80=9D but never mind. Fine, you have 85% loan-to-value, etc.[2] The rule s=
ays that it=E2=80=99s okay if the plan =E2=80=9CSpecified the amount of sec=
urities to be purchased or sold and the price at which and the date on whic=
h the securities were to be purchased or sold=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CIncluded=
 a written formula or algorithm, or computer program, for determining the a=
mount of securities to be purchased or sold and the price at which and the =
date on which the securities were to be purchased or sold.=E2=80=9D It can =
also just give discretion to your broker or other agent, as long as the bro=
ker doesn=E2=80=99t get any inside information, though in practice this see=
ms less common and less desirable than having a deterministic formula.[3] T=
his is an all-or-none thing, though; the rule says that if you trade after =
you have =E2=80=9Caltered or deviated from the contract, instruction, or pl=
an to purchase or sell securities (whether by changing the amount, price, o=
r timing of the purchase or sale),=E2=80=9D then you don=E2=80=99t get the =
protection of a 10b5-1 plan. So if you have a plan to sell 10,000 shares, y=
ou can=E2=80=99t cancel half of it and sell 5,000 shares; it=E2=80=99s all =
or nothing.
