 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">has a Times column</a> about how the venture-subsidized MoviePass econom=
y has disappeared and companies like Uber now charge almost the full cost o=
f their services:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is stil=
l plenty of irrationality in the market, and some start-ups still burn huge=
 piles of money in search of growth. But as these companies mature, they se=
em to be discovering the benefits of financial discipline. Uber lost only $=
108 million in the first quarter of 2021 =E2=80=94 a vast improvement, beli=
eve it or not, over the same quarter last year, when it lost $3 billion, an=
d both it and Lyft have pledged to become profitable on an adjusted basis t=
his year.</p></blockquote><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quo=
t;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; fo=
nt-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; paddi=
ng-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Archegos</h2><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic story of Archegos Capital Management, the fa=
mily office of former hedge-fund manager Bill Hwang, is that it bought a ha=
ndful of stocks using highly leveraged total return swaps, and then those s=
tocks went up a lot, and then they rapidly went down a lot. When they went =
down, some of Archegos=E2=80=99s prime brokers =E2=80=94=C2=A0who funded it=
s bets using total return swaps =E2=80=94=C2=A0couldn=E2=80=99t sell the st=
ocks in time and lost billions of dollars.=C2=A0From the beginning, there w=
as something slightly mysterious about this story. One of Archegos=E2=80=99=
s biggest stocks was ViacomCBS Inc., which hit a high of $100.34 on March 2=
2. By a week later, March 29, it had collapsed to $45.01; Archegos=E2=80=99=
s prime brokers were frantically selling the stock to close out their highl=
y leveraged positions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But just two months =
earlier ViacomCBS had also been trading around $45. Last year, when Archego=
s seems to have accumulated much of its ViacomCBS position, it was trading =
in the $20s and $30s. Archegos=E2=80=99s other positions had similar trajec=
tories. It is not <em>obvious=C2=A0</em>that everyone would blow up when a =
stock that Archegos bought for $30 fell back to $45. Forty-five=C2=A0is mor=
e than 30! Archegos was <em>up </em>on its trades.=C2=A0As <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24088975.258366/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDUvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zLWFyY=
2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhcmQtZm9yLWJhbmtz/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB11a1eb09" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> I wrote</a> when we first discussed Archegos[1]:</p><blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing about margin lending is that if you borr=
ow money to buy stocks, and your stocks go up, you automatically deleverage=
. If you use $15 of your own money and borrow $85 from your broker to buy $=
100 worth of stock,=C2=A0you have 85% leverage; if the stock then goes up t=
o $200, you are down to 42.5% leverage. You still owe your broker $85, but =
now you have $200 worth of stock. If the stock then falls by 25% to $150, t=
hat=E2=80=99s fine: You are still in the black, and your broker still has a=
mple security for its loan.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e thing that happened here is not just that Archegos made very levered bets=
 on some stocks. It=E2=80=99s that it did that, and those bets paid off, an=
d Archegos then=C2=A0<em>took its winnings off the table</em>, so that when=
 the stocks went down again there was no collateral left. In my example, yo=
u would go to your broker and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99m up, hand me $85 =
of my winnings, you can keep the other $30 as collateral.=E2=80=9D And then=
 if the stock does fall back to $150, the broker is in the red.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What did Archegos do with those winnings? I assumed at=
 the time, and I guess I still do assume, that it plowed them all back into=
 more levered bets on more stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0that part of the reason Vi=
acomCBS and Archegos=E2=80=99s other stocks went up so much so fast is that=
 it kept buying more of them. I assumed that Archegos had no more money lyi=
ng around, and that when it ultimately collapsed it was in part because Arc=
hegos couldn=E2=80=99t come up with more money to buy its share of a Viacom=
CBS stock offering.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it=E2=80=99s =
not entirely clear, and you could imagine another answer. You could imagine=
 Archegos distributing the cash to=C2=A0Hwang. And then when the banks went=
 to Archegos to ask for more money (to buy ViacomCBS shares, or for margin =
calls), Archegos could have said =E2=80=9Cnope sorry cupboard is bare,=E2=
=80=9D and Archegos would go to zero and the banks would lose money and Hwa=
ng would keep whatever he took out. I have no reason to think this happened=
 and it seems a little unlikely. Part of me is rooting for it though.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a Wall Street Journal story title=
d =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2408897=
5.258366/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9pbnNpZGUtY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZX=
MtNS01LWJpbGxpb24tYnJlYWtkb3duLWFyY2hlZ29zLTExNjIzMDcyNzEzP21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJ=
nJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe8a4a340" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Inside Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s $5.5 Bi=
llion Breakdown</a>,=E2=80=9D about how Credit Suisse Group AG lost so much=
 money on Archegos. One thing it does is describe when and how Archegos too=
k a lot of money off the table:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Days before Archegos blew up, ViacomCBS and Discovery stocks hit new highs=
. Around the middle of March, Credit Suisse released margin payments back t=
o the fund, the people said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Returning coll=
ateral might be a normal thing to do for a client with a diverse portfolio =
of holdings that had risen in value. But in the Archegos case, it was a pro=
blem because most of what it held was in a handful of stocks. This created =
special risks since any one stock falling could torpedo the firm.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Archegos also was making highly leveraged bets on so=
me of the same stocks with other investment banks. Credit Suisse wasn=E2=80=
=99t aware of those moves, according to Credit Suisse executives.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank wasn=E2=80=99t fully assessing its risks in=
 the stocks being so concentrated by single name and sector, according to t=
he current and former people at the bank.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">From Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s perspective, the problem here is t=
hat Archegos asked for its winnings and, instead of saying =E2=80=9Chang on=
 you might still lose, we=E2=80=99re gonna keep=C2=A0that money for a minut=
e,=E2=80=9D Credit Suisse paid them out. Other banks use =E2=80=9Ca more so=
phisticated =E2=80=98dynamic margining=E2=80=99 system that would draw on a=
dditional real-time factors beyond price, such as volatility and concentrat=
ion risk,=E2=80=9D which lets them hold more collateral when markets get we=
ird, and which here would have let Credit Suisse say no when Archegos asked=
 for its money.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But from my perspecti=
ve the more interesting question is: What did Archegos do with the money th=
at Credit Suisse sent it in mid-March? About a week later, Archegos=E2=80=
=99s stocks were crashing and its banks were panicking; Archegos was not me=
eting margin calls and the banks were losing money. In the intervening week=
, was Archegos rolling its bets into bigger bets, pushing up the prices to =
unsustainable levels and leaving it with no cash to meet margin calls? Or w=
as it taking profits, stuffing cash into suitcases, and preparing to calmly=
 ride out the storm that was coming for its banks?</p>
