<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">10b5-1 plans</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ev=
eryone knows how you can abuse 10b5-1 plans, right? Corporate executives ar=
e not supposed to trade their company=E2=80=99s stock when they have inside=
 information. This is sort of a hard rule to follow, since corporate execut=
ives are constantly getting inside information to do their jobs, and someti=
mes they need to sell stock to pay for their kids=E2=80=99 college or whate=
ver.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So U.S. securities law has=C2=A0a rule=
, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24088975.258366/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xMGI1LTE/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB18505f4d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">Rule 10b5-1(c)</a>, which says that an executive can set =
up a plan to automatically trade stock. The idea is that, when you=C2=A0<em=
>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>have inside information =E2=80=94=C2=A0say a few d=
ays after the company releases earnings, when everything that you know is (=
in theory) public =E2=80=94=C2=A0you set up a plan that says =E2=80=9CI wil=
l sell 10,000 shares a month for the next 12 months=E2=80=9D or whatever. Y=
ou can make the plan a lot more complicated; it can say things like =E2=80=
=9Cif the stock is above $100 I will sell 10,000 shares per month, if it=E2=
=80=99s between $80 and $100 I=E2=80=99ll sell 5,000 shares, if it=E2=80=99=
s below 80 I=E2=80=99ll sell 1,000 shares,=E2=80=9D etc.; it can have all s=
orts of detailed instructions for your broker for different eventualities.[=
2] The point is you sign the plan, you give it to your broker, and then you=
r broker sells the stock for you without any further input. So you are free=
 to learn material nonpublic information about your company as part of your=
 job, and your broker is free to sell your stock to pay for your=C2=A0kids=
=E2=80=99 college. Sensible rule.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People ar=
e very suspicious of these plans. For one thing, people often doubt that ex=
ecutives are=C2=A0actually<em> </em>=E2=80=9Cclean=E2=80=9D of material non=
public information when they enter into 10b5-1 plans. Which is fair enough;=
 if you run a company you always know something that the public doesn=E2=80=
=99t. My view is that there has to be=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>way for execu=
tives to sell stock while remaining employed at their companies, and 10b5-1=
 is a reasonable way to do it, but in any particular case you might wonder =
if the executive set up the plan in order to dump stock before bad news com=
es out.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, these plans alwa=
ys seem to take people by surprise? Like a company will announce bad news, =
and people will notice that the executives sold stock before the announceme=
nt, and the executives will say =E2=80=9Cwell that was pursuant to a 10b5-1=
 plan,=E2=80=9D and articles about their sales will quote that explanation =
but in a grudging suspicious way. Like the order of events will be (1) exec=
utive enters a 10b5-1 plan, (2) executive sells stock automatically, (3) co=
mpany announces bad news; but=C2=A0the=C2=A0<em>public </em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and the media, and shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0will experience that in reve=
rse. First they will see the bad news, then they will get the shocking info=
rmation that the executives were=C2=A0<em>selling stock=C2=A0</em>ahead of =
the bad news, and finally they will get the executives=E2=80=99=C2=A0lame e=
xplanation that they had a 10b5-1 plan. It might be better if the executive=
s announced the 10b5-1 plans in advance.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Finally, there is the classic way to abuse 10b5-1 plans:</p><ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In March, you have no nonpublic information, b=
ut you know that you <em>will=C2=A0</em>get nonpublic information in May an=
d announce it in June. You have a drug trial that will produce positive or =
negative news, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You sign up a =
10b5-1 plan in March to sell all your stock at the end of May.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At the beginning of May, you get the drug tria=
l results.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they are good, you c=
ancel the 10b5-1 plan and keep your stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">If they are bad, you do nothing and the 10b5-1 plan automatically =
sells all your stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In June, you=
 announce the results. If they=E2=80=99re good, the stock you kept goes up.=
 If they=E2=80=99re bad, the stock you sold goes down.</li></ol><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The trick is that you are required to be clean of materia=
l nonpublic information when you=C2=A0<em>enter=C2=A0</em>a 10b5-1 plan, bu=
t=C2=A0not when you=C2=A0<em>cancel=C2=A0</em>it. You can cancel it for any=
 reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0your kids dropped out of college, you feel like it, =
etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and because canceling a 10b5-1 plan is not a=C2=A0<em>t=
rade</em>, it=E2=80=99s not <em>insider trading</em>.[3]=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The really advanced move is:</p><ol style=3D"list-styl=
e-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">Again, in March you are =E2=80=9Cclean=E2=80=9D but know th=
at there will be news in May that will be announced in June.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You sign up a 10b5-1 plan to sell all your stock=
 on May 25.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You sign up=C2=A0<em>a=
nother=C2=A0</em>10b5-1 plan to=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>a bunch of stock on =
May 30.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CWhat, I am doing =
some complicated tax planning, don=E2=80=99t worry about it.=E2=80=9D</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At the beginning of May you get the re=
sults.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You cancel one plan and do =
the other one: If the results are good, you cancel the sale and do the buy;=
 if they=E2=80=99re bad, you cancel the buy and do the sale.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Announce the results, profit, etc.</li></ol><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be clear, these classic abuses are absolutely n=
ot allowed. The rule says that a 10b5-1 plan is only a defense to insider t=
rading if it =E2=80=9Cwas given or entered into in good faith and not as pa=
rt of a plan or scheme to evade the prohibitions of this section,=E2=80=9D =
and most securities lawyers will tell you that if you set up a 10b5-1 plan =
intending to cancel it if you get good news =E2=80=94=C2=A0or set up offset=
ting plans intending to cancel one depending on the news =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
n that is not =E2=80=9Cgood faith.=E2=80=9D (Not legal advice!) Still, thes=
e things are not easy to check, you can probably get away with it once, etc=
., and the whole thing is just viewed with a lot of suspicion by a lot of p=
eople.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Including, now, <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24088975.258366/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLm=
NvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZWNzLWdhcnktZ2Vuc2xlci1zcGVha3MtYXQtd3NqLWV2ZW50LTExNjIzM=
DcwMDk5P21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62de8f63" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Gary Gensler</=
a>, the chairman of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Speaking Monday at The Wall Street Journa=
l=E2=80=99s CFO Network event, SEC Chairman Gary Gensler said he is seeking=
 to revise rules that govern the arrangements, known as 10b5-1 plans. =E2=
=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Gensler suggested Monday that ru=
le changes are now due. =E2=80=9CIn my view, these plans have led to real c=
racks in our insider-trading regime,=E2=80=9D he said.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/24088975.258366/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3NwZWVjaC9n=
ZW5zbGVyLWNmby1uZXR3b3JrLTIwMjEtMDYtMDc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3ac58d44" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the text o=
f his speech</a>, which suggests four changes:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-t=
ype: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Required =E2=80=9Cfour- to six-month cooling-off periods=E2=80=
=9D between the time an executive adopts a plan and the time when she can s=
tart selling, to make sure that she was really clean of inside information.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Limitations on canceling plans, t=
o avoid the classic abuse:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CIn my view, canceling a plan may b=
e as economically significant as carrying out an actual transaction. That=
=E2=80=99s because material nonpublic information might influence an inside=
r=E2=80=99s decision to cancel an order to sell.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Disclosure requirements, so that shareholders know=
 about 10b5-1 plans before the executives dump all their shares.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CA limit on the number of 10b5-1 pla=
ns,=E2=80=9D to avoid the advanced move I suggested above: =E2=80=9CWith th=
e ability to enter into multiple plans, and potentially to cancel them, ins=
iders might mistakenly think they have a =E2=80=98free option=E2=80=99 to p=
ick amongst favorable plans as they please.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">I tend to think these concerns are a little overblown, and =
that anyone who actually entered into multiple plans and then freely cancel=
ed them based on inside information would get in trouble anyway. (=E2=80=9C=
Make no mistake,=E2=80=9D says Gensler:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAs the rule stands to=
day, canceling or amending any 10b5-1 plans calls into question whether the=
y were entered into in good faith.=E2=80=9D) But these concerns=C2=A0<em>ar=
e=C2=A0</em>widely held, and people=C2=A0<em>are </em>suspicious of 10b5-1 =
plans, and I don=E2=80=99t think it does much harm to address their suspici=
ons.</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot=
;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; ma=
rgin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Dave</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
=E2=80=99m sorry, this is not big news and I have nothing interesting to sa=
y about it, but this is the first I=E2=80=99ve heard of it and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24088975.258366/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9tYXJrLWN1YmFuLWJhY2tlZC1wZXJzb25hbC1maW5hbmNlLWFwc=
C1kYXZlLXRvLWdvLXB1YmxpYy1pbi00LWJpbGxpb24tc3BhYy1kZWFsLTExNjIzMDg1MzA0P21v=
